    readTime: '3 min',
    summary: "Scientists warn that not getting enough sleep is causing serious health problems worldwide.",
    content: `Scientists are calling [sleep deprivation] one of the biggest health problems of the modern world. Studies show that one in three adults in developed countries does not get enough sleep. The [recommended] amount is seven to nine hours per night for adults.

The [consequences] of poor sleep are serious and wide-ranging. In the short term, lack of sleep affects [concentration], mood, and reaction time. Tired drivers cause thousands of accidents every year. In the long term, [chronic] sleep deprivation is linked to heart disease, diabetes, obesity, and [weakened] [immune] function.

Surprisingly, sleeping less does not make us more [productive]. Research shows that people who sleep seven to eight hours actually perform better at work than those who regularly sleep less than six hours. The brain uses sleep to [consolidate] memories, process emotions, and clear waste products that accumulate during the day.

Many factors contribute to poor sleep. Modern technology is a major [culprit]. The blue light from phone and computer screens [interferes] with the production of [melatonin], the hormone that tells the body it is time to sleep. Checking social media or emails before bed stimulates the brain at a time when it should be relaxing.

Work culture also plays a role. In many countries, working long hours and sleeping little is seen as a sign of [dedication] and [ambition]. This attitude is particularly common in the United States and Japan. Experts say this attitude needs to change.

"Sleep is not a [luxury] — it is a [biological] [necessity]," said Professor Emma Wilson of Oxford University. "We would never [celebrate] someone for not eating or not drinking water. We should stop [celebrating] people for not sleeping."`,
