    readTime: '4 min',
    summary: 'Scientists discover microplastics in human blood, lungs, and even unborn babies.',
    content: `Scientists have made a deeply [alarming] discovery: microscopic pieces of plastic — known as [microplastics] — have been found in human blood, lungs, breast milk, and even in the [placentas] of unborn babies. The findings suggest that plastic [contamination] has [penetrated] every corner of the natural world, including the human body.

Microplastics are tiny fragments, less than five millimetres in size, that result from the [breakdown] of larger plastic items. They are also [intentionally] [manufactured] at a microscopic scale for use in cosmetics, cleaning products, and [synthetic] clothing. When clothes made from [polyester] or [nylon] are washed, they release hundreds of thousands of [microscopic] fibres into the water system.

The health [implications] are still being studied, but early research raises serious concerns. Laboratory studies have shown that microplastics can [accumulate] in [tissues] and [organs], [triggering] [inflammatory] responses. Some [compounds] used in plastic [manufacturing] — including [bisphenol A] and certain [phthalates] — are known [endocrine] [disruptors], meaning they [interfere] with the body's hormone system.

Every year, humanity [produces] around 400 million tonnes of plastic, of which less than 10% is [recycled]. The remainder ends up in [landfill], is [incinerated], or — [crucially] — [escapes] into the environment. The ocean now contains an estimated 170 trillion pieces of plastic.

[Environmentalists] and scientists are calling for urgent action. Several countries have banned single-use plastics such as straws, bags, and cutlery. The United Nations is [negotiating] a [global] [treaty] on plastic [pollution] — what some are calling "the plastic [equivalent] of the Paris [Agreement]".

"We created a material that lasts forever and then we used it to make things designed to be thrown away after a single use," said Dr Rachel Morgan, a marine [biologist] at the University of Exeter. "The [consequences] of that decision are now [literally] inside us."`,
